# Architecture & Code Organization (React)

For the full View module layer model, tier patterns, folder layout, naming conventions, and examples, see `.cursor/docs/frontend/react-module-architecture.md`.

## Pattern Reuse

- When creating a new hook, provider, or resource, examine sibling Views with the same suffix to match folder placement and API contract
- When adding to an extensible pattern (providers, cell renderers, resources), name and scope new artifacts at the same category level as siblings, not narrowly for a single use case
- Prefer reusing existing patterns and registration points (Provider, resource ports, query key factories) over inventing new ones. Check how similar Views are already wired before creating new infrastructure

## Module Layering

- Before adding code to a shared hook or component, verify the layering by checking existing imports. Ensure the change respects the dependency direction
- `ui` must not import `dto/` or HTTP clients directly вҖ” go through hooks

## Hook Responsibility

- Do not add new methods to an existing hook based on a superficial name match. Read the hook's existing return value and callers to verify its actual responsibility
- Do not couple UI components to an implementation detail (e.g. fetch URL, mock flag) when a stable port (`FooResource`) exists

# Frontend View Architecture (React + TypeScript)

> Architectural patterns for **View + react-ts** projects: each screen or functional area is a **View module** вҖ” a self-contained vertical slice with a clear separation of concerns (contract вҶ’ logic вҶ’ I/O вҶ’ UI).
>
> **Principle:** use **React idioms** вҖ” hooks, Context/Provider, TanStack Query, pure functions, colocation. Do not mirror backend framework mechanics (DI containers, global stores, framework-specific module systems) in the frontend unless the project already standardizes on them.

---

## 1. Layer Model

Each non-trivial View is divided into concentric layers. **api/model is the innermost layer** вҖ” the public contract everything else depends on. Dependencies always point **inward**.

